ax-height: 311px;"><div class="relative z-0 flex max-w-full"><div id="code-block-viewer" dir="ltr" class="q9tKkq_viewer cm-editor z-10 light:cm-light dark:cm-light flex h-full w-full flex-col items-stretch ͼ5 ͼj"><div class="cm-scroller"><div class="cm-content q9tKkq_readonly"><span>## Step 3.2 — Isolating Event ID 4688 in Splunk</span><br><br><span>### Action Performed</span><br><span>Searched Splunk for Windows Security Event ID 4688 using:</span><br><span>`index=* sourcetype=XmlWinEventLog:Security EventID=4688`</span><br><br><span>### Purpose</span><br><span>To isolate process creation events from the broader Windows Security logs and confirm that Splunk can show execution activity from Windows hosts in the lab.</span><br><br><span>### Result</span><br><span>The broader Windows Security search confirmed that Event ID 4688 exists in the environment. The next search focuses only on Event ID 4688 to review process creation activity directly.</span><br><br><span>### SOC Meaning</span><br><span>Event ID 4688 is a high-value telemetry source for SOC analysts because it records the creation of new processes. This helps with detection of suspicious tools, PowerShell activity, command execution, malware launch, and attacker reconnaissance behavior.</span><br><br><span>### Analyst Observation</span><br><span>Filtering to Event ID 4688 is the foundation for process execution monitoring and later suspicious command detection.</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class=""><div class="" style="width: 100%; transform: none;"></div></div></div></div></div></pre>
