ax-height: 311px;"><div class="relative z-0 flex max-w-full"><div id="code-block-viewer" dir="ltr" class="q9tKkq_viewer cm-editor z-10 light:cm-light dark:cm-light flex h-full w-full flex-col items-stretch ͼ5 ͼj"><div class="cm-scroller"><div class="cm-content q9tKkq_readonly"><span>## Step 3.2 — Isolating Process Creation Events</span><br><br><span>After confirming that Windows Security logs were present in Splunk, the next step was to isolate **Event ID 4688**, which represents new process creation on Windows systems.</span><br><br><span>The search used was:</span><br><br><span>`index=* sourcetype=XmlWinEventLog:Security EventID=4688`</span><br><br><span>This step is important because process creation telemetry is one of the most valuable data sources for SOC analysts. It allows visibility into what programs are being launched on monitored systems and supports detection of suspicious execution activity such as PowerShell abuse, command prompt usage, reconnaissance commands, and malware execution.</span><br><br><span>This search marks the beginning of direct process execution analysis in Stage 3.</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class=""><div class="" style="width: 100%; transform: none;"></div></div></div></div></div></pre>
